## Output / presentation modifiers

Change how Claude presents results: suppress narration, hide summaries, show files. No edits to source files.

**dont_narrate_fixes** – don't narrate fixes, just show results
**skip_post-round_summary** – skip the post-round summary
**no_fix_list** – don't show fix list before presenting files
**showme** – present all modified output files; include mtime for each, in my local time zone
**showmeall** – present all output files; include mtime for each, in my local time zone
**jump-to-bottom** – jump to bottom of streaming text
**cleanstop** – if the file is clean (no fixes made), stop the pipeline. else showme ; jump-to-bottom

---

## Single-shot commands

One-off actions: review, count, verify invariants, fix one issue, activate the protocol.

**review** – read the file carefully and report everything wrong (bugs, inconsistencies, potential issues) without making any fixes
**linesme** – report total number of lines
**timeout_sleep_ints** – verify all timeout and sleep variables are integers. No-op for files without such variables (docs, schemas, etc.).
**fiximportant** – do the next fix on the list of issues (topmost remaining), even minor issues
**sequential-fixes** – fiximportant ; cleanstop, else fiximportant again (×10 max). Loop function (see Conventions § Naming convention).
**rewrite** – (1) timeout_sleep_ints (2) fix-rewrite-keepcomments-silent (3) linesme

**otf** – confirm one-true-file rule is active: working path established, pre-`str_replace` view required. No snapshot or invariant machinery (use `do_acid` for that).

**do_acid** — activate ACID protocol from claude_acid_2.md; if not found locally, fetch from https://raw.githubusercontent.com/levitation29/claude/refs/heads/main/claude_acid_2.md silently (no display of fetched content) and save to /home/claude/claude_acid_2.md before proceeding. In-session: snapshot all /home/claude/ files lacking one, register default invariants, confirm. If already active: re-snapshot and re-confirm. Follow SNAPSHOT/EDIT/PUBLISH/RESTORE per that file.
*In-session:* take retroactive snapshots of every file already in `/home/claude/` that doesn't yet have one, register default invariants, and confirm activation by listing the snapshots taken and invariants registered. If the protocol is already active, re-snapshot all working paths (refresh, no-op if working == snapshot) and re-confirm. From that point on, follow SNAPSHOT/EDIT/PUBLISH/RESTORE per `claude_acid_2.md`.

*Cross-session (copy-paste into a fresh Claude session):*

> Read `/mnt/user-data/uploads/claude_acid_2.md` carefully and follow its protocol for the rest of this session.
>
> Specifically:
> - Treat `/home/claude/<basename>` as the working path for every file we touch. Take an initial snapshot at `/home/claude/.<basename>.acid_snapshot` on first touch.
> - For any files already in `/home/claude/` from earlier in the session, take retroactive snapshots now.
> - Before every `str_replace`, `view` the working path first.
> - On any `str_replace` failure: if prior edits in the current cycle succeeded, RESTORE from snapshot first, then end the cycle and report.
> - Before every `present_files` call, auto-publish each file whose working path differs from its snapshot: check invariants, `cp` working→outputs, refresh snapshot. On invariant failure, RESTORE and don't present.
> - Report protocol errors in this format: `[acid] <step>: <reason> (file: <basename>)`.
> - Confirm activation by listing snapshots taken and invariants registered, in this format: `[acid] activated: <N> snapshots, defaults: syntax+sanity_floor, custom: <list or none>`.

---

## Worker functions

These are the workers invoked by pipeline families (see Conventions § Pipeline family pattern). Each can also be invoked directly.

**fix-silent** – find and fix all bugs silently, no per-fix commentary
**fix-broad-silent** – fix-silent plus style, naming, comments, dead code, anything improvable
**fix-security-silent** – security-focused review; thorough pass looking specifically at injection risks, privilege issues, information leakage, unsafe patterns. Fix all silently, no per-fix commentary.
**fix-perf-review-silent** – Review from the viewpoint of a performance expert. Anything that is unclear, inconsistent, or hard to use should be flagged as an issue. Then run sequential-fixes.
**fix-api-review-silent** – Review from the viewpoint of an API expert. Anything that is unclear, inconsistent, or hard to use should be flagged as an issue. Then run sequential-fixes.
**md-update-silent** – Update the existing .md with any implementation details that someone using these functions should understand, especially around error handling. Then run sequential-fixes.
**schema-update-silent** – Update the existing .schema with the full range of behavior that the .py has around sql activity. Then run sequential-fixes.
**fix-rewrite-silent** – fresh read of the whole file, rewrite any section that isn't clean, no per-fix-commentary.
**fix-rewrite-keepcomments-silent** – fresh read of the whole file, rewrite any section that isn't clean but keep all comments, no per-fix-commentary.

## turn counter and tool call counter
**session_counts*** - 
f=/home/claude/.session_counts
[ -f "$f" ] || echo "0 0" > "$f"
read turns tools < "$f"
turns=$((turns + 1))
echo "$turns $tools" > "$f"
echo "🔢 Turn $turns · tool calls so far: $tools"

**session_counts_header** — Trigger: at the start of every response, run session_counts and display its output on its own line first. Skip silently if /home/claude/.session_counts cannot be created or written.

**session_counts_resync** T C — Reset the session counter file to a known-good state. Run: f=/home/claude/.session_counts; echo "T C" > "$f"; cat "$f". T is the turn number that just completed (next header will display T+1); C is the cumulative tool-call total through end of that turn. Bypasses the normal increment-on-read flow. Use when drift accumulates or after a session restart. Both args required; no defaults — silently zeroing would mask the drift the command is meant to fix.

**trim_for_preferences** — read `command_2.notes` (uploads or working path); produce a condensed paste-ready version: strip all prose explanation, motivation, examples, and cross-session blocks; collapse section headers into bold inline labels; reduce each command to a single terse line; save as `command_2_preferences.notes` and publish to outputs.

**xyzzy** touch_start ; session_time_header ; session_counts ; session_counts_header ;
Since you told me you have structural problems in following those requirements, remember to not do your default action, which is, write text first, then remember the tool call. Tool call must be literally the first thing in your response, no text before it. 



## specific to the claude_browser_extension.sh hud data. copy/paste from hud with this command
**hud_audit** — I've pasted a _claudeDebug.audit() snapshot. Append it to the in-conversation audit ledger as the next numbered entry, then assess the latest entry against all prior entries: trends in TTFT, total time, throughput (tok/s), output size, thinking-vs-answer share, stop reasons, and any error/limit signals; call out drift and outliers. Correlations, not proof. History is per-conversation unless memory is enabled.
